<DOC><DOCNO> AP880809-0075 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1129EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0527fusedMondaytoapologizeforconCentralUnitedStates08-09 0769</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0789</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Rip Though Central United States</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Leads with 18 grafs to UPDATE with lightning death, new infoon Tropical Storm Beryl, picking up 12th graf pvs, `Today'sforecast ....'^By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   Fierce thunderstorms ranged from Michigan to Kansas today aftermuch of the central United States was belted by storms bringinglarge hail, drenching rains and winds that blew out windows andleveled trees and power poles.   Lightning killed a teen-age girl and critically injured herfriend at a Racine, Wis., park.   In the South, Tropical Storm Beryl moved across New Orleanstoday, prompting the National Weather Service to alert 16 coastalparishes for possibly heavy rains.   Strong storms ripped through northeast Kansas and northernMissouri early today but the intensity of many storms began to fadein early morning.   In southern Wisconsin, high winds toppled trees across Highway24 at Muskego, while in Vernon, winds gusted to 60 mph. Streets inLake Geneva were flooded by the torrential rain, and at least onefunnel cloud was sighted.   Strong thunderstorm winds also scattered trees at Roscoe andRockton, Ill., as well as in Plainview, Donahue and Walcott, Iowa.Power poles fell in high winds at West Liberty, Iowa.   In Kansas City, Mo., strong winds brought down trees and blewout windows.   Hershey, Neb., was blasted by winds up to 60 mph and hail thesize of golf balls.   The storms also brought a deluge of rain. More than 2 inchesfell at Kearney, Mo., and Madrid, Kan.   In Chicago, rain forced officials to cut short the Cubs' firstnight baseball game at Wrigley Field.   ``This is typical,'' said one disgruntled fan. ``It doesn't rainall summer long, and then on the first night game ever, it has torain.''   In Racine, witnesses told police that a lightning bolt hit atree at Lincoln Park, then apparently traveled through the groundand struck the two girls Monday afternoon.   Karla Kay Hedding, 17, died immediately, said Thomas Cloyd,assistant Racine County medical examiner. Her friend, who was notidentified, was listed in critical condition at Milwaukee CountyMedical Complex.   As Beryl, the Atlantic hurricane season's second named storm,moved over New Orleans, forecasters said its movement raised hopesthat it might dissipate.   Earlier, several coastal communities were evacuated as thestorm, which has already forced thousands of oil workers from theiroffshore rigs, intensified off the Louisiana-Mississippi Gulf Coast.   At 8 a.m. EDT today, the Beryl's center was just northwest ofNew Orleans at latitude 30.2 north and longitude 90.3 west. Highestsustained winds were 50 mph.   Warnings were in effect from Morgan City, La., to Pensacola, Fla.   Thunderstorms spawned by Beryl poured heavy rain along the GulfCoast from southeast Louisiana to Mobile, Ala. Biloxi, Miss.,received more than 3 inches of rain early today.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms fromFlorida and southern Georgia across southern Louisiana; numerousthunderstorms from northwest Florida to western Louisiana fromTropical Storm Beryl; scattered showers and thunderstorms throughlower Michigan, southeast Wisconsin, northern Indiana, Illinois,much of Missouri, Kansas, northern Vermont to northern Maine; andfair weather throughout the rest of the nation.   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s over Upper Michigan,northwest Washington and parts of the California coast; in the 90sor higher from southern New England to Florida, from the OhioValley across to the central Gulf of Mexico coast, over the lowerhalf of the Mississippi Valley, through eastern Montana, throughthe central Pacific coast and the Great Basin, between 100 degreesand 105 degrees over Oklahoma, central Texas and across the desertSouthwest; in the 80s through the rest of the nation.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 44degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 92 degrees atPhoenix, Ariz..   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 77 partly cloudy; Boston 74 fair; Buffalo 70fair; Charleston, S.C. 76 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 68 fair;Cleveland 69 fair; Detroit 77 cloudy; Miami 77 partly cloudy; NewYork -- foggy; Philadelphia 72 fair; Pittsburgh 65 fair; Portland,Maine 68 fair; Washington 72 fair.   _Central: Bismarck 51 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 87 fair; Denver 63fair; Des Moines 72 partly cloudy; Indianapolis 73 hazy; KansasCity 75 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 66 fair; Nashville 75 fair;New Orleans 75 showers; St. Louis 84 partly cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 67 fair; Anchorage 59 partly cloudy; LasVegas 78 fair; Los Angeles 63 partly cloudy; Phoenix 89 fair; SaltLake City 61 fair; San Diego 66 fair; San Francisco 54 fair;Seattle 63 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 77 cloudy; Toronto 73 fair.</TEXT></DOC>